    <h1 class="entry-title">5 challenges facing the field service manager</h1>
		

<!-- BEGIN .entry-meta-header-->
<div class="entry-meta-header">
    <span class="published">June 6, 2014</span>
    <!-- END .entry-meta-header -->
</div>


<!-- BEGIN .entry-content -->
<div class="entry-content">
	<p>Managing a large mobile workforce can be a daunting task, but the key to success is identifying the greatest obstacles and finding workable solutions.</p>
<p><span id="more-28"></span></p>
<h2>Challenge #1 &#8211; coordination</h2>
<p>There will be days when it feels like the whole world is against the field service manager. Workers will call in sick, appointments will be cancelled without notice and roads will be jam-packed with traffic. Disruptions like this to the everyday schedule can be a logistical nightmare to resolve if you don&#8217;t have the systems in place to shift resources in real-time.</p>
<p>[Tweet &#8220;There will be days when it feels like the whole world is against the field service manager. &#8220;]</p>
<h2>Challenge #2 &#8211; productivity</h2>
<p>Poor productivity from workers in the field can be difficult to identify, particularly if timesheets are only submitted at the end of the working day, or in the worst cases, the end of the week. It&#8217;s important for the field service manager to always know exactly how long workers are spending on a job so productively can be constantly reviewed and optimised.</p>
<h2>Challenge #3 &#8211; lunch time</h2>
<p>How can a field worker possibly know what time they&#8217;ll take breaks on any given day? Every job is different and unexpected issues are certain to arise. But the combination of extended time spent on job sites and unscheduled breaks can cause delays and customer complaints. Management must have the ability to respond and reassign jobs accordingly.</p>
<h2>Challenge #4 &#8211; paperwork</h2>
<p>If there&#8217;s one thing the field worker hates, it&#8217;s paperwork. Customer information, job descriptions, contracts and signatures, it makes life harder than it needs to be and can often result in errors and poorly documented jobs. Fortunately, the evolution of smartphones and tablet computers means it&#8217;s possible to minmise paperwork for workers with the right software solution.</p>
<h2>Challenge #5 &#8211; scheduling</h2>
<p>Whether field operatives have set hours or work in shift patterns, it can be a constant source of discomfort to allocate jobs and manage their schedules. Again, this problem can be easily resolved with the right management software, which can handle the job for you with the click of a button.</p>
<p>Master the field and all of these challenges by signing up with <a href="http://www.workforce.fm/" >Workforce.FM &#8211; industry leading field service management software</a>.</p>
